 childhood and illness. Offers a critique of existing explanations for the gender bias of witch-trials, and a new explanation as to why most witches were women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWitchcraftzGermanyzRothenburg ob der TauberxHistoryy16th century. 0aWitchcraftzGermanyzRothenburg ob der TauberxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aRothenburg.  aaccusations.  aalleged witches.  aconfessions.  aearly modern Europe.  aexecution.  alegal records.  awitch-crazes.  awitch-trials.  awitchcraft.1 aRowlands, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137982zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137982zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137982/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA